/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/factual/string-theory/landscape-problem.md:10:The string theory landscape refers to the enormous number of possible vacuum solutions (false vacua) that arise from flux compactifications of the extra dimensions. This multiplicity of solutions is widely considered the most serious obstacle to extracting unique predictions from string theory.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/factual/string-theory/landscape-problem.md:14:The canonical estimate of ~10^500 distinct vacua was established by Michael Douglas (2004), based on statistics of flux compactifications. The number arises combinatorially: a Calabi-Yau manifold in 6 dimensions has approximately 500 topological cycles, and quantized fluxes through each cycle can take multiple discrete values (e.g., 0 through 9), giving roughly 10^500 possibilities. Earlier work by Lerche, Lust, and Schellekens (1986-87) on heterotic string vacua had already indicated very large numbers (~10^1500). More recent estimates place lower bounds at 10^272,000.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/factual/string-theory/landscape-problem.md:18:Vacua are fundamentally stable states. Each valid configuration of compactified extra dimensions and flux choices represents a legitimate, stable vacuum state with its own particle physics, coupling constants, and cosmological constant.
