/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/agents/library/factual/gravitize-the-quantum/thooft-cellular-automaton.md:12:Quantum mechanics is not fundamental but is a mathematical tool for describing an underlying deterministic system. At the Planck scale, physics is governed by a classical cellular automaton — a discrete, deterministic dynamical system on a lattice. QM emerges as the effective description when coarse-graining over Planck-scale details.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/instances/nature-of-time/strategies/strategy-001/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:71:The standard story in physics goes like this: The fundamental laws (Newton's laws, the Schrödinger equation, Einstein's field equations) are all time-reversible. Irreversibility — the arrow of time — is merely statistical. It arises because we happen to live in a universe that started in a low-entropy state, and entropy increases because there are more high-entropy microstates than low-entropy ones. On this view, irreversibility is not fundamental; it is an artifact of initial conditions and coarse-graining.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/instances/nature-of-time/strategies/strategy-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:30:**The connection to undecidability:** Israeli and Goldenfeld (2004) showed the relationship is subtle — some properties of computationally irreducible systems *are* predictable (coarse-grained properties may be computationally reducible even when microscopic details are not). This is important: computational irreducibility is not absolute. It is a property of specific questions about specific systems. But for the microscopic state — the full detailed configuration — irreducibility holds for the vast majority of non-trivial systems.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/instances/nature-of-time/strategies/strategy-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:88:3. **Observer theory:** The specific physics we observe (special relativity, quantum mechanics, general relativity) emerges not from the rules themselves but from the interaction between the computational irreducibility of the underlying process and our computational boundedness as observers. We must "coarse-grain" the ruliad to perceive it, and the specific way we do this (sequentially in time, locally in space) gives rise to the laws of physics.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/instances/nature-of-time/strategies/strategy-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:95:- The role of the observer as a computationally bounded entity that must coarse-grain the underlying computation is a deep insight. It connects the epistemic and ontological aspects of time.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/instances/nature-of-time/strategies/strategy-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:202:**Best response:** Wolfram's multiway system addresses this partially: quantum mechanics emerges not from a single computational thread but from a branching multiway graph where all possible computational paths are followed simultaneously. The "single thread" of time that we experience is a coarse-graining — what a computationally bounded observer perceives when they cannot track all branches individually. Time is still one-dimensional because the observer's experience is sequential, even if the underlying computation is branching.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/instances/nature-of-time/strategies/strategy-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:335:- **Israeli & Goldenfeld (2004):** Showed some properties of computationally irreducible systems are predictable (computational reducibility in coarse-grained properties).
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/instances/nature-of-time/strategies/strategy-002/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:70:**Core claim:** Time IS the real, irreducible process of entropy production and dissipative self-organization. Irreversibility is not a statistical artifact of coarse-graining but a fundamental feature of nature. Time's arrow isn't imposed on thermodynamics — it is thermodynamics.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/instances/nature-of-time/strategies/strategy-002/explorations/exploration-002/REPORT.md:96:**(c) Prigogine's physics of becoming:** The irreversibility of actualization has a specific physical mechanism. In nonintegrable dynamical systems (which include most physically interesting systems), Poincaré resonances create genuine singularities that prevent the construction of unitary transformations diagonalizing the dynamics. This means the evolution cannot be decomposed into time-reversible trajectories — irreversibility is built into the fundamental dynamics, not imposed by coarse-graining or initial conditions. Prigogine's non-unitary transformations formalize this: the algebra of observables for such systems admits only semigroup (one-way) evolution, not group (reversible) evolution. "The inclusion of thermodynamic irreversibility through a non-unitary transformation theory leads to a deep alteration of the structure of dynamics. We are led from groups to semigroups, from trajectories to processes."
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/instances/quantum-gravity/interpretations/interpretation-3.md:53:The metaphor of a hologram is overused and not quite right. A hologram is a 2D surface encoding 3D information through interference patterns. The QG+F picture is something stranger: a 2D structure that *becomes* effectively 4-dimensional (3 space + 1 time) through the dynamics of the theory itself. The extra dimensions are not encoded on the surface; they *grow out of it* as you zoom out. They are artifacts of coarse-graining. They are real in the same way that a coastline has a definite length — which is to say, only at a particular resolution, and the answer changes if you look more closely.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/instances/barandes-stochastic/library-inbox/exploration-002-stochastic-programs-comparison.md:257:**The relationship:** These are complementary, not equivalent. CH's consistency condition is a condition on which SETS OF HISTORIES can receive classical probability assignments (a selection criterion applied to histories). Barandes' indivisibility is a structural property of the transition kernel (a classification criterion for stochastic processes). They're measuring different things: CH asks "for this quantum system, which coarse-grained description is internally consistent?" while Barandes asks "which stochastic processes correspond to quantum systems?"
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-atlas/execution/instances/barandes-stochastic/library-inbox/exploration-002-stochastic-programs-comparison.md:287:**Both frameworks hit the same philosophical wall**: QM does not uniquely specify a classical description. CH calls this the realm selection problem; Barandes avoids naming it but acknowledges it (via phase freedom). The parallel is substantive: both are expressing the fact that quantum mechanics admits many inequivalent classical coarse-grainings, none of which is preferred.
